---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Himanshu Kher — CFO, strategist, and writer on finance & AI"
  description="Himanshu Kher: two decades in finance and strategy across trading, fintech, and digital assets — Nomura, BCG, Barclays IB, IG, and now a CFO role. Now writing on the CFO function, AI, and capital strategy at signal-to-noise.co."
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-[720px] px-6 py-16 sm:py-24">
    <header class="mb-12 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-[240px_1fr] gap-8 sm:gap-10 items-center">
      <img
        src="/img/himanshu-portrait.webp"
        alt="Black-and-white editorial portrait of Himanshu Kher"
        width="600"
        height="900"
        loading="eager"
        class="w-full max-w-[200px] sm:max-w-none h-auto rounded-lg border border-divider/60"
      />
      <div>
        <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-widest text-accent mb-6">About</p>
        <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-semibold tracking-tight leading-tight text-fg">
          Finding signal in finance.
        </h1>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="space-y-6 text-lg text-fg leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        I'm Himanshu — currently the Chief Financial Officer of a global online
        trading firm based in London. Before that, I spent two decades building
        treasury, risk, and capital-markets functions across some of the most
        demanding institutions in the City: <strong>IG</strong>,
        <strong>Barclays Investment Bank</strong>,
        <strong>The Boston Consulting Group</strong>, and
        <strong>Nomura</strong>.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-fg mt-12 mb-4">
        What I think the job actually is
      </h2>
      <p>
        The most useful thing a finance person does in a fast-moving business
        isn't reporting — it's <em>framing</em>. Translating between a board
        that wants certainty and an operation where the answer hasn't been
        built yet. Holding the strategic question open while the tactical one
        gets solved. Knowing which numbers should bend and which shouldn't.
      </p>

      <p>
        That framing is what I'm best at, and it's what this site is about.
        I'm a pragmatist — more interested in what actually works than in what
        the textbook says, more drawn to figuring something out than to
        defending what already exists.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-fg mt-12 mb-4">
        Background
      </h2>
      <p>
        Engineer by training (<strong>IIT Kharagpur</strong>), then a Masters in
        Finance at <strong>London Business School</strong>. I started on the M&amp;A
        and ECM desks at Nomura, traded equity derivatives at BNP Paribas, advised
        global financial institutions on risk and treasury at PwC, ran point on
        strategy projects at BCG, and from there settled into the CFO / Treasurer
        track — Barclays IB, IG, LMAX, and on to my current role. Along the way
        I picked up the ACT's MCT Advanced Diploma and Wharton's CFO programme.
      </p>

      <p>
        Based in London. Hindi and Marathi at home; English everywhere else.
        Outside work: cricket (still play, still love it), Indian classical
        music, and a long-standing focus on health and fitness.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-fg mt-12 mb-4">
        What I write about
      </h2>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
        <li>
          Strategy in fast-moving markets — how firms in finance, technology, digital
          assets, and trading actually make decisions when the data is incomplete and the
          rules are being written in real time
        </li>
        <li>
          Operating-model design — where to centralise, where to leave loose, what to
          automate, what to leave human
        </li>
        <li>
          Capital, risk, and structure — where the money actually goes, where the risk
          actually sits, why the deck and the operation diverge
        </li>
        <li>Occasional notes on the craft — building, hiring, writing, reading</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-fg mt-12 mb-4">
        What this site is for
      </h2>
      <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2">
        <li><strong>A portfolio</strong> of my writings.</li>
        <li>
          <strong>A thinking platform</strong> — short takes when there's a sharp point,
          longer pieces when there's a real model worth showing.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>A home base</strong> for the people whose work I want to be near.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p class="mt-12">
        If you want to talk about an idea, a piece of work, or something you are reading,
        <a
          href="/contact"
          class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover transition-colors"
        >here's the best way</a>.
      </p>

      <p class="text-sm text-muted mt-12 pt-6 border-t border-divider/60">
        Views on this site are my own, not those of any current or former employer.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
